    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-08-08T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-08-08T17:00:00-05:00" n="269"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d269">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">891.24/232a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in Iran</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dreyfus</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-08-08T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >August 8, 1942—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>205. Your 250 and 251, August 5.<note n="20" xml:id="d269fn20">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_151">pp. 151</ref> and <ref
                            target="#pg_152">152</ref>, respectively.</note> The Iranian Minister
                    here has reached an agreement with Joseph P. Sheridan for the latter’s
                    appointment as Food and Supply Adviser to the Iranian Government. Minister has
                    cabled Tehran for approval of the terms agreed upon. Because of the various
                    inoculations required for air travel to the Near East, Sheridan will necessarily
                    be delayed here until early <pb facs="0256" n="244" xml:id="pg_244"/> September,
                    but it is hoped he will be able to depart for Tehran immediately after September
                    7.</p>
                <p>In your discretion you may inform the Prime Minister<note n="21"
                        xml:id="d269fn21">Ahmad Qavam.</note> that the Department considers Sheridan
                    a very able man and believes that if given full cooperation by the Iranian
                    Government he will be of great assistance in solving the pressing supply
                    problems confronting Iran. During his stay in Washington he will make a study of
                    the situation in so far as information is available here and will investigate
                    the questions involved in obtaining supplies from the United States.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
